With the rise of streaming, it=E2=80=99s obvious you don=E2=80=99t own the =
shows you watch on Netflix or Hulu. You lose access to content the minute y=
our bill is overdue.

When it comes to the TV on which you watch that show, however, it sure feel=
s like you own it. After all, you bought the device and installed it in you=
r living room or bedroom. No one tells you which streaming service to use o=
r which Blu-ray player to hook up. You own it, so you control how it is use=
d.

Loss of control is the canary in the coal mine of ownership. At the end of =
March, that canary=E2=80=99s song wavered as Walmart announced [https://ful=
u-foundation.ghost.io/r/61987cad?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] =
its new Vizio televisions will require customers to sign in to Walmart acco=
unts to access smart TV features.

This move, one of the most aggressive in undermining owners=E2=80=99 contro=
l of their televisions to date, is the latest in an industry with a long hi=
story of surveillance.


The history of watching us watch TV

Since the invention of the television, companies have wanted to know what A=
mericans were watching. The A.C. Nielsen Company, now known as Nielsen IQ [=
https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/faea4588?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98=
315f6032b], first created television ratings in 1950. In exchange for allow=
ing the company to install meters that monitored when a TV was in use and t=
o which channel it was tuned, Nielsen would pay a group of demographically =
representative families to track what they watched. Monitoring viewing habi=
ts paid off as the resulting data served a wealthy market: the advertising =
industry.

As technology has progressed, so have the ways that Nielsen and others trac=
k what people watch. The development of automatic content recognition (ACR)=
=E2=80=94which companies now owned by Roku [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.i=
o/r/8877d130?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b], Vizio [https://fulu=
-foundation.ghost.io/r/36468934?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b], =
and Nielsen [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/5660fdb1?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-=
4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] began to patent as early as 2008=E2=80=94added TV m=
anufacturers to the mix.











=C2=A0




[https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/c0761cfd?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f9=
8315f6032b]




ACR allows TV makers and other surveillance businesses to more accurately t=
rack watching habits at a far greater scale. Instead of making assessments =
based on the channel to which an owner=E2=80=99s set is tuned, ACR takes sn=
apshots of audio or video as often as every 10 milliseconds [https://fulu-f=
oundation.ghost.io/r/cc19c638?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] fro=
m any media source connected to your TV [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r=
/e8578074?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b], and compares them agai=
nst a broader video database. Because the technology is built into devices =
and =E2=80=98consent=E2=80=99 to be tracked is often buried in the terms of=
 service [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/213701e8?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bf=
d-bc68-f98315f6032b] required to use smart features, manufacturers and thei=
r ACR partners are able to track what nearly every smart TV viewer is watch=
ing.

After a 2017 Federal Trade Commission complaint [https://fulu-foundation.gh=
ost.io/r/a0b9279f?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] against Vizio f=
or collecting data without consent,more TV makers have moved to allow consu=
mers to opt out of ACR tracking.But many don=E2=80=99t make it easy.Manufac=
turers often obscure the software=E2=80=99s invasive nature by naming ACR t=
echnology to imply improved user experiences and hiding the opt-out option =
[https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/8c796992?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f9=
8315f6032b]4-10 clicks [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/7d8c749f?m=3Db50=
3a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] into the settings menu.

Even if a user has previously opted out [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r=
/7403fe80?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b], data-sharing permissio=
ns are also often re-enabled [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/a5c42b7f?m=
=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b]during software updates. Those wish=
ing to take more complete measures, such as permanently deleting ACR softwa=
re, risk bricking their device.

As a result, companies gather up to 100 billion data points [https://fulu-f=
oundation.ghost.io/r/5d0fba86?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] eac=
h day,which they use to build advertising profiles about individual viewers=
 that can include information such as suspected race, political leanings, [=
https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/436848bf?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98=
315f6032b]religious beliefs, age, [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/43325=
a15?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] and geographic location [http=
s://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/2beab88e?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f=
6032b]. [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/51bd5855?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd=
-bc68-f98315f6032b]


TV makers are in the surveillance business, and business is a-booming

Fueled by ACR data, the connected TV (CTV) advertising business is extremel=
y lucrative. One estimate [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/50750ee4?m=3D=
b503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] predicted the total CTV ad spend to h=
it $33 billion in 2025 and grow to $47 billion by 2028.Walmart CFO John Dav=
id Rainey recently credited [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/0edd466e?m=
=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] the company=E2=80=99s 2024 [https:=
//fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/9941d43c?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f60=
32b] acquisition of Vizio for the =E2=80=9Ctriple-digit growth in advertisi=
ng,=E2=80=9Dwhich raked in roughly $6.4 billion in profit in 2025 and now r=
epresents roughly a fifth [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/8205b288?m=3D=
b503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] of the company=E2=80=99s operating in=
come.

Requiring new Vizio TV owners to log in with their Walmart account shows th=
e company plans to take its surveillance even further. Its stated goal [htt=
ps://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/5cff8a71?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315=
f6032b] of this integration is to remove the disconnect between =E2=80=9Cco=
mmerce and measurement=E2=80=9D and create an =E2=80=9Cidentity framework a=
cross devices, connecting streaming engagement directly with retail interac=
tion.=E2=80=9D

In other words, simply tracking what you=E2=80=99re watching and serving yo=
u targeted ads isn=E2=80=99t enough. Walmart wants to use that information =
to create an endless feedback loop that enables you to buy, buy, buy. And W=
almart is not alone=E2=80=94competitors [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r=
/29c641d6?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] are integrati [https://=
fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/9379e64d?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032=
b]ng [https://fulu-foundation.ghost.io/r/bf3f08f3?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc=
68-f98315f6032b] advertising and e-commerce by partnering [https://fulu-fou=
ndation.ghost.io/r/86f6e45b?m=3Db503a08a-c4e6-4bfd-bc68-f98315f6032b] with =
Amazon to more precisely track and target audiences.


Why can manufacturers peep on the device you own?

Americans might not think twice about signing into an additional account wh=
en they set up a new TV. But if your neighbor stood outside your window whi=
le you watched Friends, you would probably close your curtains and lock you=
r door. If he showed up the next day to try to sell you a Central Perk mug,=
 you might look into getting a restraining order.

While you can=E2=80=99t see them, what TV manufacturers and their ACR partn=
ers are doing with your data is just as creepy. Once your TV is connected t=
o the internet, Amazon or Walmart might as well be sitting on your couch.

Today=E2=80=99s decline of ownership isn=E2=80=99t just about media=E2=80=
=94it=E2=80=99s now also about the device its consumed on. Invasive data co=
llection practices exploit consumers=E2=80=99 personal data while overly br=
oad terms of service and anti-consumer design make it difficult to stop its=
 flow. Without the ability to strip such technology out of the devices they=
 own, consumers are faced with a double edged sword: protect their privacy,=
 or use the smart features they paid for.



















